== Discussion

*Evaluating joint trajectory and angle accuracy*

This study aimed to: 1) Examine the accuracy of a low-cost, six-camera markerless motion capture system in capturing gait kinematics across increasing walking speed and 2)  Characterize the effect of three pose estimation backends (MediaPipe, RTMPose, and ViTPose) on the reconstructed 3D data. Overall, the markerless system demonstrated good agreement with the marker-based reference across joint trajectories and sagittal kinematics, with errors comparable to those reported in prior validation studies.

Joint trajectory errors were generally under 30 mm and sagittal joint angle errors below 5°, consistent with ranges reported across other markerless validation studies (6-30 mm for trajectories, 2-11° for sagittal angles) @ripicComparisonThreedimensionalKinematics2023 @nakanoEvaluation3DMarkerless2020 @kankoAssessmentSpatiotemporalGait2021 @uhlrichOpenCapHumanMovement2023. The hip, often identified as a particularly challenging joint with reported trajectory errors of 30-50 mm and flexion/extension errors of 11°  @kankoConcurrentAssessmentGait2021 @needhamAccuracySeveralPose2021, exhibited mean error under 25 mm in all directions across all trackers in the present study and flexion/extension error under 4.5°.
Overall, the kinematic errors observed in this study fall within the 2-5° range that McGinley et al. suggest is suitable for clinical work, given consideration during interpretation @mcginleyReliabilityThreedimensionalKinematic2009.
 
SPM testing showed consistent regions of significant difference in early stance phase in knee and ankle kinematics across all speeds. These deviations align with the loading response phase of gait, during which the knee undergoes transient flexion as a method of shock absorption and the ankle plantarflexes slightly during the first rocker phase. This suggests that these rapid, impact related motions may be more difficult to track accurately. Additionally, heel strike and impact absorption are known to cause skin surface movement that propagates throughout the lower limb @painSoftTissueMotion2002, and marker-based motion capture can be particularly susceptible to soft tissue artifacts during the landing phases of movement @KinematicDifferencesOptical2013. As such, while marker-based data serve as the reference in this study, they do not represent true joint centers, but rather the most accurate available approximation.

*Evaluating gait parameter accuracy*

Spatiotemporal gait parameters, pooled across all speeds, demonstrated minimal bias and strong agreement with the reference. Agreement was lowest for the swing phase duration (ICC ≈ 0.90), consistent with findings from Kanko et al. who reported similar LoA ranges and reduced swing phase agreement @kankoAssessmentSpatiotemporalGait2021. This pattern likely reflects higher foot velocity during swing that may be more difficult to capture accurately. Additionally, at a sampling rate of 30 Hz, temporal resolution is limited to approximately 33 ms increments. As the majority of detected gait event timing errors were within one frame, this may obscure finer differences in event timing. Higher frame rate systems may therefore provide improved temporal resolution.


*The impact of speed on accuracy*

As a general pattern, spatial metrics (i.e., joint position and angle error, stride length, step length) demonstrated clear sensitivity to walking speed, while temporal metrics (i.e., heel strike and toe off timing error, stance duration, swing duration) appeared comparatively stable. However, temporal metrics should be interpreted within the context of the system's temporal resolution limits, as mentioned above. 

Increasing walking speed resulted in larger joint position and angle errors, particularly in the anteroposterior and vertical directions at distal joints. Higher segment velocities likely amplify frame-to-frame tracking error, contributing to reduced agreement. However, the effect of speed on accuracy was not uniform, but varied across joints and axes, suggesting segment-specific sensitivity to speed.

*Tracker-dependent changes in 3D data*

MediaPipe SPM analysis revealed regions of significant difference flanking peak hip extension and knee flexion, with cluster magnitude and duration decreasing at higher walking speeds. These changes may be explained by the One-Euro filter @casiez1FilterSimple2012 utilized in MediaPipe landmark smoothing. The One-Euro filter is an adaptive low-pass filter that adjusts its cutoff frequency based on signal velocity - applying stronger smoothing during slower motion and less smoothing during faster motion, balancing lag and jitter. The suprathreshold clusters correspond to phases of rapid change in joint angular velocity (i.e., transitions into and out of peak excursions) where the filter must adjust its cutoff in response to changing signal dynamics. This adjustment introduces temporal lag, which manifests as systematic deviation from the reference. At slower walking speeds, overall signal velocities are lower, resulting in heavier smoothing and greater lag at these transitions. At faster speeds, the filter permits higher-frequency signals to pass through, reducing lag and producing closer agreement with the reference.

ViTPose-derived reconstructions required a median scaling factor of 0.98 (range: 0.96-0.98) to align with the reference, indicating an apparent size difference of 2-4%. Trajectory error was disproportionately elevated in the vertical direction relative to other axes, suggesting this difference is primarily vertical rather than isotropic. Despite this, ViTPose-derived stride length and step length exhibited the lowest bias among all the trackers. These metrics are primarily calculated in the anteroposterior direction, further supporting the presence of anisotropic scaling. These errors may also propogate into joint angle estimates. ViTPose-derived ankle angle exhibited consistent plantarflexion offset and persistent suprathreshold SPM clusters across the gait cycle. Given the sensitivity of foot segment orientation to small positional errors, this may be explained by vertical positioning error at the toe. Although ViTPose-derived estimates were generally accurate for hip and knee kinematics, parameters that depend on vertical positioning (e.g., minimum toe clearance) should be interpreted with caution.

The exact source of this spatial offset remains unclear, but one structural distinction warrants consideration. RTMPose and MediaPipe, whose derived data both exhibited near 1.0 scaling factors, use convolutional neural network (CNN) based architectures that build spatial relationships between pixels over many layers, which helps encode spatial structure into the architecture. ViTPose employs a vision transformer backbone that lacks these spatial inductive biases and relies more heavily on learning spatial relationships from data @takahashiComparisonVisionTransformers2024 @LearningSpatialDecay, which could potentially lead to the observed scaling issues. However, whether the architectural difference causes theses issues are unconfirmed, and testing with different model configurations would be needed to isolate the source of the discrepancy.

RTMPose-derived reconstructions were generally consistent across spatial, kinematic, and spatiotemporal gait metrics, without the speed-dependent temporal effects observed in MediaPipe or the spatial bias observed in ViTPose-derived reconstructions. Ankle kinematics were tracked with the lowest error among the evaluated methods. 

Validation studies have typically attributed accuracy differences between pose estimators to training dataset composition. While this is an important factor, the present findings also suggest that architectural and implementation-level differences (i.e., temporal filtering strategy and backbone topology) can influence the reconstructed data in ways that are not often characterized. The range of walking speeds examined in this study was instrumental in revealing these patterns, as speed-dependent effects would not be apparent in single-speed validations. This underscores the value of evaluating markerless systems across varied movement conditions.